O:9:"MagpieRSS":23:{s:6:"parser";i:0;s:12:"current_item";a:0:{}s:5:"items";a:25:{i:0;a:9:{s:4:"guid";s:45:"http://mightybear.livejournal.com/202954.html";s:7:"pubdate";s:29:"Mon, 24 Aug 2015 11:20:33 GMT";s:5:"title";s:29:"Teaching animals to be polite";s:4:"link";s:45:"http://mightybear.livejournal.com/202954.html";s:11:"description";s:2348:"To me, it always seemed like a smart idea to train dogs to wait politely for their food rather than diving in the moment it's accessible. Especially since I tend to get dogs that are larger than average. <br /><br />Cats are more difficult to train and so I haven't bothered with Strike. As a result, every morning I get to enjoy Chase's dialogue with Strike as he attempts to pour food in his bowl while Strike is lunging into the way of things.  Chase patiently explains to Strike, before the whole ordeal begins, that it would be in his best interest to stay out of the way - he will get his food faster that way!  And then, as Strike ignores this sage advice, Chase reminds him with loving exasperation that he can't put food in the bowl when there is a cat head or body in the way, and wouldn't he just like to get down to the business of eating?<br /><br />But, of course, I am working with Mercy on manners.  She knows how to sit, so I have been teaching her to sit and then "Waaaaait", which if she does not, I take the food away until she properly sits and waits.  I do this with her food and also treats.<br /><br />As you're training your puppy to wait politely, you start out with very short duration waiting, so they understand that they will be getting their treats soon enough, and there is no cause for panic!<br /><br />As the puppy is learning the way of things, you slowly extend the waiting time, or make the food more attractive to them, or put it much more temptingly close to them.  If you do very well, you end up with a dog <a href="http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2036492/Hilarious-YouTube-footage-patient-dog-balancing-biscuits-treats-nose.html" rel="nofollow">this well trained</a>.  I am not quite that hard-core, though.<br /><br />But Mercy DOES get extra challenge training in the form of Strike, who also likes dog treats as it turns out.  So Mercy is sitting and waiting like a good girl, but then Strike sees what's going on and thinks "AWW, HECK YEAH, FREE TREATS!" and Mercy has to wait as I fend a very excited cat off while at the same time praising the puppy for her patience.<br /><br />The cat and puppy are so cute together, in general.  Strike playfully pounces on Mercy, who is now quite a bit larger than the cat.  I wonder if Strike will continue to play with Mercy when she's 10x Strike-size.";s:8:"comments";s:45:"http://mightybear.livejournal.com/202954.html";s:2:"lj";a:2:{s:8:"security";s:6:"public";s:11:"reply-count";s:1:"0";}s:7:"summary";s:2348:"To me, it always seemed like a smart idea to train dogs to wait politely for their food rather than diving in the moment it's accessible. Especially since I tend to get dogs that are larger than average. <br /><br />Cats are more difficult to train and so I haven't bothered with Strike. As a result, every morning I get to enjoy Chase's dialogue with Strike as he attempts to pour food in his bowl while Strike is lunging into the way of things.  Chase patiently explains to Strike, before the whole ordeal begins, that it would be in his best interest to stay out of the way - he will get his food faster that way!  And then, as Strike ignores this sage advice, Chase reminds him with loving exasperation that he can't put food in the bowl when there is a cat head or body in the way, and wouldn't he just like to get down to the business of eating?<br /><br />But, of course, I am working with Mercy on manners.  She knows how to sit, so I have been teaching her to sit and then "Waaaaait", which if she does not, I take the food away until she properly sits and waits.  I do this with her food and also treats.<br /><br />As you're training your puppy to wait politely, you start out with very short duration waiting, so they understand that they will be getting their treats soon enough, and there is no cause for panic!<br /><br />As the puppy is learning the way of things, you slowly extend the waiting time, or make the food more attractive to them, or put it much more temptingly close to them.  If you do very well, you end up with a dog <a href="http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2036492/Hilarious-YouTube-footage-patient-dog-balancing-biscuits-treats-nose.html" rel="nofollow">this well trained</a>.  I am not quite that hard-core, though.<br /><br />But Mercy DOES get extra challenge training in the form of Strike, who also likes dog treats as it turns out.  So Mercy is sitting and waiting like a good girl, but then Strike sees what's going on and thinks "AWW, HECK YEAH, FREE TREATS!" and Mercy has to wait as I fend a very excited cat off while at the same time praising the puppy for her patience.<br /><br />The cat and puppy are so cute together, in general.  Strike playfully pounces on Mercy, who is now quite a bit larger than the cat.  I wonder if Strike will continue to play with Mercy when she's 10x Strike-size.";s:14:"date_timestamp";i:1440415233;}i:1;a:9:{s:4:"guid";s:45:"http://mightybear.livejournal.com/202639.html";s:7:"pubdate";s:29:"Sat, 22 Aug 2015 14:36:14 GMT";s:5:"title";s:25:"Connor's studying hurdles";s:4:"link";s:45:"http://mightybear.livejournal.com/202639.html";s:11:"description";s:1988:"Connor's teacher's blog said they had a test on European geography coming up.<br /><br />It is Saturday.  I told him that given our shared memory issues, it's a good idea to study a little bit for that test daily rather than cramming at the last minute (or not, as the case may be, because he's conveniently left all his materials at school the day before the test.)<br /><br />He tells me that he doesn't have his materials to study from, because he's left his notebook at school.  I remind him I've told him to take his science/ss notebook home daily because we need to make note of what he's learning and potentially study.<br /><br />He says "Ah well, it wouldn't make a difference anyway because I didn't take notes."  I asked why.  He said "Because I didn't know we'd be tested on the material."<br /><br />I said "I have told you before, any time a teacher is telling you facts and concepts, you will be tested on it.  The point of tests is to make sure you're absorbing what's going on in the classroom.  So everything you hear is test material."<br /><br />I then asked if this material was covered in the workbooks (supplemental materials) that we bought at the start of the year.  He said it was.  I said "GREAT.  I bought you extra copies of those books to keep at home for just such occasions.  We'll look there."<br /><br />He told me we can't do that because he forgot to take one of his books home the other day and so he did the worksheet in his extra workbook and then took the extra workbook to school and didn't bring it home.  -.-<br /><br />I asked him if he remembered ANYTHING they talked about in class on this subject, and he said no.<br /><br />So then I say "Well, there's only so much European geography.  In the absence of a study guide or notes, we will hedge our bets and learn all of it!"<br /><br />At this point Connor had a miraculous recovery of memory and was able to narrow the field down quite a bit.<br /><br />It's going to be an awesome year! =P";s:8:"comments";s:45:"http://mightybear.livejournal.com/202639.html";s:2:"lj";a:2:{s:8:"security";s:6:"public";s:11:"reply-count";s:1:"0";}s:7:"summary";s:1988:"Connor's teacher's blog said they had a test on European geography coming up.<br /><br />It is Saturday.  I told him that given our shared memory issues, it's a good idea to study a little bit for that test daily rather than cramming at the last minute (or not, as the case may be, because he's conveniently left all his materials at school the day 