d interesting. &nbsp;Ah well. &nbsp;Try once - give up! ;) &nbsp;I&#39;ll teach him a lesson later on by showing that there are some pretty neat apps out there to help with this kind of thing ;)<br /><br />Once he got the library spreasheet in place, he started asking clever questions, such as if there was a way he could program the spreadsheet to calculate the due date of the book automatically, and how he could get it to e-mail people to remind them a book is due. &nbsp;I am pleased to see that these questions occur naturally to him. &nbsp;I wonder if it is the generation, who just expects that computers can make anything easier, or if he&#39;s also inherited his parents&#39; inclinations towards automation.<br /><br />On a funny note, during this whole process he became obsessed with the row/column marker situation - letters for columns and numbers for rows. &nbsp;He wanted to know how to change the &quot;A, B, C&quot; up top to something more meaningful. &nbsp;I eventually had to give up explaining that even if he could do such a thing, he would not want to, and there are other ways to denote column headers. &nbsp;He was really irritated that the rows were not indicating the number of books available directly, since he put the column headers on row 1.<br /><br />I am guessing he&#39;s about ready to take on databases, since he has seen the limitations of spreadsheets. ;)";s:8:"comments";s:45:"http://mightybear.livejournal.com/197176.html";s:2:"lj";a:2:{s:8:"security";s:6:"public";s:11:"reply-count";s:1:"0";}s:7:"summary";s:3002:"I have been in super-organization mode since our new room&#39;s closets have become usable. &nbsp;Part of this is me purging the house of things we no longer need, so we are in a state of taking everything off of every shelf and out of every drawer and sorting them into boxes or back where they should belong.<br /><br />So I have been having the kids sort out books they no longer want, one cube at a time, from the Ikea bookshelf in the g